<BaseLayout
  title="Foundations — grimbergIT"
  description="For manual testers making the jump into automation. Command line, IDE, Git, and the first real automated test."
>
  <article class="surface">
    <p class="eyebrow">Workshop · 01</p>
    <h1>Foundations</h1>

    <p>
      For manual testers making the jump into automation. The people who write the tests that catch
      the real bugs — and who now need the tooling around a codebase to keep doing it. This workshop
      is the on-ramp: no assumptions about prior developer experience, and no shortcuts around the
      parts that matter.
    </p>

    <h2>What we cover</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>The command line.</strong> Enough to move around, run scripts, and read what the machine
        is telling you. Not a Unix philosophy tour — just the muscle memory you need every day.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>An IDE.</strong> How to set one up, how to search a codebase, how to use the debugger
        and the run configuration — the parts most tutorials skip past on their way to "and here's a working
        test".
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Git.</strong> Clone, branch, commit, push, pull request. The workflow every team expects
        you to know, taught in the order you actually use it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>A first automated test.</strong> One real test, written against a real application, in
        a language and framework the team already uses — so it's something you can take back to work on
        Monday.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Where to go from here.</strong> A short map of the next skills — reading code, writing
        code, choosing a framework, joining a team's practice — so the next step isn't a cliff.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Format</h2>
    <p>
      One day by default. Splittable into two half-days if the team's calendar prefers it — the
      material breaks naturally in the middle, between the tooling foundation and the first
      automated test. Also available as a multi-week cohort with homework repos between sessions,
      which suits people learning around a full-time role.
    </p>

    <h2>What you leave with</h2>
    <p>
      A working development environment, a mental model of the tools around the code (not just the
      code itself), and one real automated test written by you against a real application. Also, the
      confidence that the next test is not going to be the hard part.
    </p>

    <p>
